	abstract = {Background: Previous studies in animal models evidenced that genetic mutations of KATNAL1, resulting in dysfunction of its encoded protein, lead to male infertility through disruption of microtubule remodelling and premature germ cell exfoliation. Subsequent studies in humans also suggested a possible role of KATNAL1 singlenucleotide polymorphisms in the development of male infertility as a consequence of severe spermatogenic failure.
